  <p>For all the attention on who will win the 2026 World Cup, the tournament is quietly becoming a referendum on a less glamorous question: can online betting platforms actually keep children off them when demand surges? A new study from identity-verification firm Jumio puts numbers to the anxiety. Surveying 8,003 adults across the United States, United Kingdom, Singapore, and Mexico, it found that 63 percent worry minors will use sports betting apps during the tournament &mdash; and that 74 percent believe the responsibility for stopping them lies with the platforms and their technology providers, not with parents or the minors themselves.</p>

